	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0320">320<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0320.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">La Haie 10<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> 7<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">br.</span> 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Quoique malade depuis 8 jours, je fais cependant des efforts, non seulement pour vous acheminer lincluse pour le Congrs dont le contenu Vous mettra au fait de la suite des affaires ici, mais aussi pour r[<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">pon</span>]dre  votre faveur du 25 Aot un peu plus en dtail que je nai pu faire dans mes deux prcdentes, la 1<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> sous couvert de Mr. Th<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">s.</span> Barclay, la suivante directement  V. E. selon ladresse prescrite, esprant dapprendre, que lune &amp; lautre sont bien parvenues en vos mains.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Nous avons t dautant plus aise ici  la reception de votre susdite Lettre, que 8 ou 10 jours aprs votre dpart le bruit couroit ici, quun Paquebot allant en Angleterre, Stoit perdu. Javois cependant cach cela chez moi, pour nallarmer personne, &amp; il ny avoit que moi seul dinquiet  ce sujet, come  tous ceux o je puis pargner de la peine autres. Maintenant je vous flicite, ainsi que votre chere famille, de pouvoir me raconter les fatigues &amp; travaux passs, au milieu du calme, de la tranquillit, de la salubrit de votre belle habitation, de votre Parc de Boulogne, &amp; surtout des bras de Mad<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Adams,  laquelle nous prsentons nos respects. Veuillez aussi les faire agrer  L. E. Mess. Franklin &amp; Jepherson.</p>
        <span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0321">[321<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0321.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
        
        <span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0322">[322<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0322.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Nous ne somes pas moins mortifis que V. E. de ce que vous navez pu rsider au moins un mois ici avec Madame &amp; Mademoiselle Adams, puisque cela nous auroit procur lhonneur de leur connoissance personnelle, &amp; que nous aurions eu la satisfaction en mme temps de revoir Mr. votre fils, dont nous regrettons souvent laimable socit.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Je suis avec grand respect, / De Votre Excellence / Le trs-humble &amp; trs-obissant / serviteur</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="translation">
        <h2>TRANSLATION</h2>
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 10 September 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Although sick for the last eight days, I am nonetheless making the effort not only to forward to you the enclosed for Congress, the contents of which will inform you about the course of events here, but also to respond to your letter of 25 August in detail, which I was not able to do in my two most recent letters, the first sent in care of Mr. Thomas Barclay, the second sent directly to your excellency at the designated address. I hope to learn that both of them arrived safely in your hands.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">We were especially relieved here to receive your abovementioned letter, as eight or ten days after your departure the rumor spread here that a packet boat on its way to England had been lost. I nonetheless kept this to myself in order not to alarm anyone, and I was the only one who worried about it, as I always want to spare others from suffering. Now I congratulate you as well as your dear family on being able to recount to me past fatigues and travails in the midst of the calm, tranquility, and salubriousness of your beautiful home, your Bois de Boulogne, and above all the arms of Mrs. Adams, to whom we send our respects. Please also give them to their excellencies Messrs. Franklin and Jefferson.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">We are no less mortified than your excellency that you were not able to reside here with Mrs. and Miss Adams at least a month, because then we would have had the honor of making their personal acquaintance, and at the same time we would have had the satisfaction of seeing your son again, whose charming company we often miss.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I am with great respect your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0209-sn">
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: A S. E. M. Adams M. P. des E. U.</p>

        </div>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0209-fn-0001">1</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Dumas likely did not send this letter until 12 Sept. because he probably enclosed his 9 Sept. letter to the president of Congress, to which he appended a 12 Sept. postscript. There Dumas reported the States of Zeelands approval of a Franco-Dutch defensive alliance, with which the States General had unanimously concurred. He also enclosed a copy of the 8 Sept. memorial presented by Laurent Brenger, the Duc de La Vauguyons secretary, to the States General. There Louis XVI urged the Dutch assembly to propose terms for a negotiated settlement of the conflict with Joseph II and to avoid any action that might give offense to the Austrian emperor. In his postscript Dumas
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0323">[323<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0323.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
            added that the Comte de Vergennes had given the Dutch ministers at Versailles confidential assurances that if the French kings efforts at mediation proved unfruitful, he would employ more effective means on behalf of the Dutch Republic (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early nineteenth century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e., the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 93, III, f. 2729; No. 115B, f. 5152; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:515516). Dumas most recent letter to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> was dated 31 Aug., for which see note 2 to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0198" class="document">letter to Dumas of 25 Aug.</a>, above; Dumas also wrote on <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0204" class="document">3 Sept.</a>, above.</p>

        </div>

      </div>
